Education and schooling can have a significant impact on societal inequity. On the one hand, education has the potential to reduce existing social and structural inequities by equipping individuals with the knowledge, skills, and abilities required to function in society and improve their social and economic standing. Education can also promote social mobility and give people the chance to break free from a cycle of poverty and disadvantage. However, by reproducing social and economic inequality, education can also perpetuate existing social and structural inequities. This can occur in a variety of ways: Education access: Access to education is limited for marginalized and disadvantaged groups, which can perpetuate social and economic inequality. This can occur when schools are underfunded, lack resources, or are located in high-poverty, high-crime areas. Curriculum and instruction: By failing to provide students with the knowledge, skills, and abilities needed to function in society, or by teaching a narrow and biased version of history and culture, school curriculum and instruction can perpetuate social and economic inequality. This can occur when the curriculum is not culturally responsive and relevant, or when it is not tailored to the needs of various student groups. Tracking and streaming systems in schools can perpetuate social and economic inequality by categorizing students into different academic programs based on their perceived ability. Students from marginalized and disadvantaged groups may be placed in lower-level classes and denied access to advanced classes and opportunities as a result of this. Teacher bias: By having biases that limit the potential of students from marginalized and disadvantaged groups, teachers can perpetuate social and economic inequality. This can occur when teachers have low expectations for certain students or fail to provide them with the same opportunities and support that other students receive. To summarize, education and schooling can have significant implications for societal inequity. While education has the potential to reduce existing social and structural inequities, it also has the potential to exacerbate them. It is critical to recognize how education can perpetuate social and economic inequality and to work toward a more equitable education system that promotes social mobility and equal opportunities for all students. 